   285	### Verified Parquet.Net list-of-scalar column build (from the live spike)
   286	```csharp
   287	// schema leaf path is "chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item" (note the "/list/" segment)
   288	var fVal = (DataField)schema.GetDataFields().First(f => f.Path.ToString() == "chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item");
   289	var fInt = (DataField)schema.GetDataFields().First(f => f.Path.ToString() == "chunk/intensity/list/item");
   290	// spike measured: list item MaxDefinitionLevel = 4, MaxRepetitionLevel = 1
   291	
   292	// Per chunk row, build LeafRow entries with the existing helpers:
   293	//   present item   -> def = MaxDefinitionLevel        (4)
   294	//   null  item     -> def = MaxDefinitionLevel - 1    (3)
   295	//   rep            -> 0 for the first item of the row's list, MaxRepetitionLevel (1) thereafter
   296	int vP = fVal.MaxDefinitionLevel, vN = fVal.MaxDefinitionLevel - 1, vRep = fVal.MaxRepetitionLevel;
   297	// row whose mz_chunk_values == [delta, null, delta]:
   298	var row = MzPeakParquet.ListOf(new[]{vP, vN, vP}, new[]{true, false, true});
   299	// NestedLevels(fVal, rows) -> (defLevels, repLevels); only NON-null values go in the value Array.
   300	var (def, rep) = MzPeakParquet.NestedLevels(fVal, rows);
   301	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(fVal, nonNullDoubleValues, def, rep));
   302	```
   303	Spike round-trip output (values correct, nulls preserved):
   304	```
   305	chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item = [0.1, null, 0.3, null, 250]
   306	chunk/intensity/list/item       = [10, 20, 30, null, 99]
   307	```
   308	[VERIFIED: ran on Parquet.Net 5.0.1, net via DOTNET_ROLL_FORWARD, arch -arm64]
   309	
   310	**Streaming carries it unchanged:** the existing `Handle.WriteRowGroupAsync(schema, cols)` writes each `schema.GetDataFields()` leaf from the `cols` dictionary. List leaves are ordinary `DataField`s in that walk; no Handle change is required. The new facet stream mirrors `PointFacetStream` (buffer per scan → flush at `Cap` → `Close(finalMetadata)`), differing only in that one chunk *row* carries variable-length lists (so the cap counts chunk rows, not points). **Gotcha vs point columns:** point columns are flat (def/rep = null); chunk list columns MUST pass computed `def`/`rep` arrays. Also the value Array passed to `DataColumn` contains only the non-null elements (nulls are expressed purely via def-levels), exactly as the aux-array `data` list already does.
